segments.text: Did you even know the word cocaine?
No.
Didn't know the word cocaine.
Heroin was known, and opium.
Opium probably more so.
But again, students didn't indulge in those things.
You just didn't.
Alcohol was the drug of choice.
And I never knew of anybody on heroin or cocaine or even marijuana.
Again, marijuana being something that the lower classes dealt in marijuana, people that weren't very smart.
Let's see.
You didn't do final review your senior year.
You didn't do commissioning.
You didn't get senior boots.
I had senior boots before I was drummed out.
I did have senior boots for a brief period.
Still have them, as a matter of fact.
And you say drummed out.
Well, I could not review the contract because I had a gap.
And as far as you knew, you and others, they were looking for reasons not to have to have too many second lieutenants.
Oh, yeah.
Korea's over.
We don't need them.
So they were looking for ways to get out of it.
And truthfully, we were looking ways where we were just as happy to be out of it.
Senior ring.
Do you remember when you got it?
At ring dance.
When I got it, I got it before ring dance.
I got it between junior and senior year.
An interesting thing, when I was president of the Association of Farmer Students, I lost my senior ring.
During that year?
During that year, I lost my senior ring.
And I can't remember the name of the lady who was ring clerk forever.
But we went over and went down into the basement where she had the records.
And Buck Wirus went with me and said, Miss, this is John.
He's president of the association.
He lost his ring.
He wants to order another one.
And she said, I'll check.
And she went off into the tombs and came back with my records and on her adding machine added up ours.
And then she said, I guess it will be all right.
That wasn't all evolution, was it?
No, no, no, no, no.
What was that woman?
She was ring clerk forever.
I can't remember her name.
But she added, I'm president of the Association of Farmers.
I pay her salary.
Was there any kind of routine for you and your buddies when you got your ring that y'all did anything?
No, I got my ring.
See, today, apparently, one of the things for some people is you put it in a pitcher of beer.
They drink the whole, all the pitcher.
No, we put it in a four-pitcher.
No, we got our ring and we put it on right then.
What were your feelings about putting that ring on?
This was a symbol that it's almost over.
And the ring was respected.
And so this was the symbol that it's almost over.
And you looked forward to the ring dance to turn it around.
Yes, it was an important thing.
It was an important part of it, totally.
And when I had mine remade, I had it remade as A&M College.
But I had to have the new one.
It was by then University.
And I had mine made.
My replacement was made with college on it.
Now, did you put any shoe blacking on your rig?
No.
Because I've understood that that was what some people did.
To keep it looking new?
Yeah, yeah.
What does it mean to wear an egg?
Personal satisfaction, achievement.
It has many times produced recognition in strange places, in weird places, in other nations, and it has produced recognition.
Just spur of the moment.
And of course I have seen it and recognized people and said something to people when I would see the ring.
And it's not uncommon even today at my age.
I see it in young people and I see it in people my age.
And I always say something to them if I spot a ring somewhere.
Did you go to bonfire?
No, yes.
Where was it held?
Right in the middle of the drill field, right in front of the student center.
What was it composed of?
Trees, logs, same thing they do today.
See, once upon a time there was trash, but no trash.
No trash.
No trash in our day.
Whose job was it to put it together?
The Corps generally put it together, and work assignments were based on your position in the Corps.
So the freshmen were, we didn't have cranes.
We had a center pole with a rope on it.
And if you get enough freshmen pulling out there going that way, you can pull the log up this way.
And so freshmen were beasts of burden.
And the sophomores weren't a whole lot better.
About when did the effort begin for the bug fight?
Wood started being cut probably a month before and trimmed up so that you kept only the trunk of the tree.
And that started maybe a month earlier because we did it with axes.
We didn't do it with chainsaws.
Did bonfire seem like a serious area then?
Oh, it was, yeah, it was a joyous event.
Yeah.
Everybody there to have a good time.
Yes.
Yes.
What about Muster?
What about you as a student?
Muster held, as a student, you went to Muster, which was normally held in front of the administration building.
And so you all assembled out there on that open area toward Highway 6.
And it would be the entire student body for the muster speech and address.
Daylight address.
Daylight.
And what did that, did that have any...
It helped to, it is the thing I guess that...
that triggers you to the future when you're gone.
That one thing may be the thing that triggers you into the local club when you leave A&M.
It's muster that is the habit you develop that pulls you into the local club.
and get you to come in.
And once you get into the local club, then you have the camaraderie.
When you were an undergraduate, you heard the muster roll thing, right?
Did you hear any names that touched you?
No, nothing to be said.
I was wondering if there were any students that you had known that got killed in Korea?
Yes.
But it was so common, it was not emotional.
It's like any war.
Oh, Joe got killed.
Oh, that's tough.
Damn, he was a good fellow.
See, for me, Vietnam, to hear the name of the student that had been in my class was really tough.
But I'm talking about my age as a student.
See, now you're more mature.
You're talking about being a professor.
now, and that being more mature and more understanding.
But when it's somebody that is your age and he went off to war and you expect a percentage of them to be killed, it's, oh, that's too bad.
He was a good guy.
As you're getting ready to leave the campus professionally, how did you feel about getting a job, whether or not you were prepared for the real world?

I felt adequate and felt good because I had been through this series of things of working for a summer and a semester and going to school for a semester and working a summer and a semester and going to school for a semester.
So I had passed over that thing of obtaining and doing and going and so forth.
So it was not...
awesome to me, if you will.
I can appreciate how it can be a frightening thing, somebody coming out.
But I had passed that because I had been through that routine.
You see, it actually took me until 55 before I could actually end up with a degree in my hand, which was in 52.
Did you feel that A&M prepared you well?
Oh yes.
I still feel good about that.
Did A&M help you get a job or did you?
No, no.
I had it all lined up.
And within two years I went into business for myself and had been there ever since.
I knew where I was going.
That was all.
I knew exactly what I was going to do.
and how it was going to get from here to there.
Let's see.
A side trip.
Student nicknames, do you remember any that were funny, goofy?
I haven't stopped thinking about that.
Not in particular.
Because it seems to me in that year almost everybody had a nickname.
I was Bubba.
There were a thousand Bubbas.
Were you Bubba before you went to A&M?
Did you become Bubba later?
Yeah, I carried Bubba with me.
Oh, you carried him with you.
Yeah.
And...
I don't think of anything strange.
There were all of the usual ones, but nothing different, nothing exciting, nothing strange.
Sorry that makes for good writing, but it's...
Right now, we're getting ready to the serious part.
What did it all mean?
Are there any things that you had anticipated?
Do you think of any omissions yet?
Anything we've overlooked, forgotten, left out?
During student days,
Pascoe, we're going so far back, it's really difficult to recall.
Without your prodding, I would even have more difficulty recalling a lot of things that went on.
Was anything Hayden Boatner?
Was he the commandant all of your years?
No.
Who took over after him?
Jim something or other.
I'm sorry, but the general went on to Korea, as a matter of fact.
Boatner.
Yes.
Prison camp.
Yes.
And you all knew he would straighten it out quickly.
I knew they were in lots of trouble over there.
Who was president at A&M when you were there?
Oh, OK.
I bridged Tom Harrington and David Morgan.
Did you have any impression of them?
My roommate, the editor of the battalion, and Tom Harrington had a running hatred for each other that, of course, I got involved in.
In fact, in later years, Tom became a good friend and a man whom I thought a great deal of.
David Morgan was kind of like the paint on the wall.
Nothing outstanding about David Morgan.
And I don't even recall who followed him.
Who was dean of engineering?
The fact that you...
He was dean forever.
He was dean forever.
Gosh.
And Gilchrist had already retired.
Gilchrist was gone.
Gilchrist was gone.
Oh.
Okay, let's go to the...
I'll remember the dean of engineering.
He was dean of engineering for... even after I became active in the association's work, he was still dean of engineering.
What are the events or circumstances or whatever that make up Aggie spirit?
People.
Learning how to get along with people, learning how to meet and understand.
And when you have people with the common thing, you develop the common bond.
And it's because you have that commonality and you want to make it work.
And you do make it work.
Are there any events where these people
Oh, yes.
Every city has its own events that are ongoing.
I got active in the Fort Worth AM Club.
But let's go back.
Is this created first on the campus?
Well, it's created first.
You first have a loyalty.
I guess your first loyalty is your roommate, and you become self-protective.
And then it's your outfit or organization.
And I do the quotation marks on outfit because I am a radical and I told people at College Station 30 years ago before I was really active and I was looked down upon in 1975 because I
really screamed it from the bully pulpit that I had.
We needed desperately fraternities and sororities.
Because a fraternity is nothing but an outfit.
And I screamed it loudly and I was
strongly and loudly put down in those days.
I submit to you that I was right.
I wish we had a piece of real estate adjacent to the campus where a bunch of fraternities were.
Oh, wouldn't that be wonderful?
Wouldn't it be wonderful?
Because surely it wouldn't surprise you to find out those who live on university or college campuses make better grades than those who live off.
Those who live off, who live in an organizational setting.
Do better than those who live in an apartment house.
Absolutely.
There's somebody to turn to to wake you up, give you help.
Absolutely.
You develop that commonality, that camaraderie, that spirit, if you will, and that is what turns inward.
A&M originally got it because of its isolation.
It first developed because it's an isolated place.
Even when I was there, it was isolated.
You couldn't run down to Houston.
You couldn't run up to Dallas.
You couldn't run over to San Antonio.
Today, transportation being what it is, it's nothing to go to those places.
But in those days, you had to plan ahead, and you had to work hard, and you had to figure out what you were going to do before you could go to one of those cities.
Right now, this causes me to jump back.
Neither you nor anyone else I've interviewed has talked about riding on the train to or from College Station.
Did many students ever ride the train?
I think that's probably the only train service.
I rode the train a couple of times when I would stay to...
This was after I was senior and was ready to get married.
I rode the train back a couple of times simply because I could get the old train out of...
It left Fort Worth here, went to Dallas, and then wandered down and picked up milk all the way to Houston.
And you left here about 11 o'clock at night, and you got to College Station about 7 o'clock in the morning.
It took that long because it stopped every few feet.
It had square wheels.
I rode that train a few times, but it was a thing of convenience because I had to get down.
Serious questions.
What did it mean to you?
What has it meant to you in your life that you went there?
It's meant a great deal to me in high school because I have put a lot...
post-graduate in A&M.
I've been active in A&M affairs and still am for that matter.

I got into local club and from local club into the former student association council and from the council to the executive committee and from the executive committee to being president and from being, after I was
When I became past president, Jack Williams asked me to go on the board at Yellowstone and I did.
He asked me
to serve a number of boards.
I was part of the organization of the press, which I have loved every moment of.
If I've done anything good, it was helped to organize the press and to be a part of the press.
If I've done anything good, that was it.
Yes, it has meant a lot to me.
It has meant that I have friends everywhere and friends all over.

all stages of wealth and life and age one of the difficult things for me is to identify now with my own class because you know i i i i don't know if you remember remember niley smith he always i'm niley smith normally well niley was a friend as well as people who are still in school are friends
And that's because I have been close to it.
And I really don't have a strong identification with my class.
But A&M has been a great deal to me because it has opened up and let me see a lot of things that otherwise I would have been lost into my own personal daily routine and not be able to see.
Right now, I may be repeating the question.
What feelings do you have in your heart for A&M now?
I am planning now to try to do some work with a group that Barry Thompson organized.
A side issue to the old Target 2000 group, and I was vice chairman of that group, a side issue to that that
that got buried, I think, out of fear and concern and lack of desire was we did not look far enough.
Target 2000 group took A&M and A&M is exactly what Target 2000 designed
There was a group of us, an undercurrent, that said, somewhere out there beyond, universities are going to have to change.
Universities.
And we need to plan that now.
And so a lot was done, but not enough.
And I think that what has happened to the system recently
as increasingly new Texas A&M universities are growing is where 2000 was headed but couldn't bring itself to go there.
It is not practical to take A&M much farther than it is now in population.
And yet the A&M experience, the spirit, the ideas, the basic thoughts and so forth need to be made open to an ever increasing population.
It is important that that experience be available to ever more and more and more people.
It's in the interest of the future students.
It's in the interest of Texas that we take this idea and we expand on it.
And somehow, Texas A&M University at Canyon has to become Texas A&M University.
And Texas A&M University Kingsville has to become Texas A&M University.
And Texas A&M University Carpets has to become Texas A&M University.
And there has to be absolutely no difference between them.

and a course in the history of the war between the states, the unpleasantness, which I think is your field, the unpleasantness of the 1860s, the same course that is taught at College Station has to be taught everywhere and at the same time.

so that the benefit can be taken through video conferencing of the knowledge of Haskell-Monroe, and it can be delivered to each of these other campuses at the same hour, on the same day, out of the same book, and so forth.
Otherwise, we cannot deliver the education that we need to to the people of Texas, and we have to do that.
And so now it's time to plan again and let's look out there for 18, for 2050.
And let's be prepared and let's be there before we're in trouble for not going.
